---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'eberswalde-crater');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Eberswalde Crater location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Eberswalde Crater - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-900 to-teal-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          The distinctive inverted channels of Eberswalde Crater delta system
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL/University of Arizona</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Eberswalde Crater stands as one of Mars' most compelling examples of 
          ancient water activity, hosting the most well-preserved river delta 
          system on the planet. This 65-kilometer-diameter crater in Margaritifer 
          Terra contains what scientists call a "textbook" inverted-channel delta 
          that provides unambiguous evidence of sustained water flow and lake 
          environments on early Mars.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The crater's delta system, measuring 13 by 11 kilometers with six distinct 
          lobes, represents the first clear "smoking gun" evidence that Mars 
          experienced persistent liquid water flow over extended periods. The 
          preserved distributary network, complete with meander cutoffs and 
          inverted channels, tells the story of an ancient river system that 
          flowed into a stable lake environment.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          What makes Eberswalde truly exceptional is its preservation state - 
          erosion has inverted the original channels, creating ridges that allow 
          scientists to study the three-dimensional structure of this ancient 
          water system in unprecedented detail, making it a cornerstone site 
          for understanding Mars' hydrological past.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Crater Diameter:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">65.3 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Delta Size:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">115 km² (13×11 km)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Formation Period:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">2.0-3.5 billion years ago</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Delta Thickness:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~100 meters</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Key Feature:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Best-preserved Mars delta</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Delta System Formation Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      The Delta System: Ancient River Meets Lake
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The Eberswalde delta formed when an ancient river system flowed into 
        a stable lake environment within the crater. As the river's velocity 
        decreased upon entering the standing water, it deposited its sediment 
        load, creating the distinctive fan-shaped delta with six separate lobes 
        representing different phases of river activity.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Delta Characteristics</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Six distinct depositional lobes</li>
            <li>• Preserved distributary channel network</li>
            <li>• Meander cutoffs and oxbow features</li>
            <li>• Inverted relief preservation</li>
            <li>• Clay-rich sedimentary deposits</li>
            <li>• Evidence of varying water levels</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Lake Environment</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Paleolake level: -1400 to -1350 m</li>
            <li>• Surface area: 410-810 km²</li>
            <li>• Neutral pH conditions</li>
            <li>• Habitable environment indicators</li>
            <li>• Long-term stability evidence</li>
            <li>• Connection to regional water system</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Inverted Channel System Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Inverted Channels: Erosion Reveals Ancient Waterways
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-900/50 to-teal-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-teal-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Formation Process
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Channel inversion occurred when sediments deposited in the river 
          channels became more resistant to erosion than the surrounding 
          terrain. As the softer materials eroded away over millions of years, 
          the former channel floors were left standing as ridges, creating 
          an inverted topographic relief.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          This process preserved the three-dimensional structure of the ancient 
          river system, allowing detailed analysis of flow patterns, channel 
          migration, and depositional environments.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Scientific Value
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The inverted channels provide the first unambiguous evidence that 
          some Martian sedimentary rocks were deposited in a liquid environment. 
          The preserved morphology allows scientists to reconstruct ancient 
          flow velocities, discharge rates, and seasonal variations.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Channel measurements reveal straight and meandering paleochannels 
          with evidence of cut-and-fill sequences typical of active river systems.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Paleohydrology Reconstruction
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Detailed analysis of the channel geometry and delta structure has allowed 
        scientists to reconstruct the ancient hydrology of the Eberswalde system. 
        The river that formed this delta had channel-forming discharge rates of 
        approximately 200-400 cubic meters per second, comparable to modern 
        Earth rivers.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The system shows evidence of both event-driven flows (possibly from 
        storms or seasonal melting) and sustained base flow, indicating a 
        complex hydrological cycle that operated over timescales of thousands 
        to millions of years.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Clay Minerals and Habitability Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Clay Minerals and Ancient Habitability
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter has identified iron and magnesium smectite 
          clays within the Eberswalde delta deposits - minerals that require 
          water to form and are excellent preservers of organic materials. These 
          clays likely formed in the wet subsurface conditions of early Mars, 
          earlier than 3.5 billion years ago.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Biopreservation Potential
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Clay minerals are exceptional at preserving organic compounds and 
              potential biosignatures. The clay-rich sediments in Eberswalde 
              represent some of the best targets for detecting evidence of 
              ancient microbial life on Mars.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Neutral pH Environment
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The presence of these specific clay minerals indicates the ancient 
              lake environment had neutral pH conditions suitable for life, 
              contrasting with the acidic conditions found at many other Martian 
              locations.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Mineral Composition
        </h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Iron/Mg Smectites:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Primary</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Formation Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">>3.5 Ga</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">pH Conditions:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Neutral</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Preservation:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Excellent</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Mission History Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Mission Selection History
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Eberswalde Crater's exceptional scientific value has made it a top 
        candidate for multiple Mars exploration missions. Its well-preserved 
        delta system and potential for biosignature preservation have repeatedly 
        placed it on mission shortlists, though it has not yet been selected 
        as a primary landing site.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        <div class="border-l-4 border-yellow-500 pl-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Mars Science Laboratory</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Eberswalde was a finalist for Curiosity's landing site due to its 
            preserved delta and potential for studying ancient habitability. 
            Gale Crater was ultimately selected for its geological diversity.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Mars 2020 Consideration</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            The site was again considered for Perseverance due to its exceptional 
            biosignature preservation potential, though Jezero Crater was chosen 
            for its similar but more accessible delta system.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Future Missions</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Eberswalde remains a high-priority target for future sample return 
            missions due to its unparalleled preservation of ancient aqueous 
            environments and delta sediments.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Assessment Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/30 to-green-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-green-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">7</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            High Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-green-300">
            Proven ancient habitability with excellent resource indicators
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Proven long-term water stability</li>
            <li>• Clay-rich soils for agriculture</li>
            <li>• Neutral pH environment history</li>
            <li>• Protected crater environment</li>
            <li>• Diverse geological resources</li>
            <li>• Evidence of stable climate conditions</li>
            <li>• Natural basin for water collection</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Limited current water access</li>
            <li>• Dust accumulation in crater</li>
            <li>• Radiation exposure concerns</li>
            <li>• Temperature fluctuations</li>
            <li>• Access to surrounding terrain</li>
            <li>• Atmospheric pressure variations</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Significance Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific and Astrobiological Significance
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Astrobiology Cornerstone
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Eberswalde Crater represents one of the most compelling locations for 
          the search for ancient life on Mars. The combination of preserved 
          organic-friendly clay minerals, evidence of long-term water stability, 
          and neutral pH conditions creates an ideal target for biosignature 
          detection. The delta's layered sediments act as a natural archive 
          of environmental conditions during Mars' potentially habitable period.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Planetary Hydrological Archive
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The intact source-to-sink fluvial system at Eberswalde provides 
          unparalleled insights into Mars' ancient water cycle. The preserved 
          catchment-to-delta system allows scientists to study the complete 
          hydrological process, from watershed erosion to sediment deposition, 
          offering crucial data for understanding how water shaped the Martian 
          landscape billions of years ago.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration Opportunities
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Despite not being selected for recent missions, Eberswalde Crater 
        remains one of Mars' highest-priority exploration targets. Its exceptional 
        preservation of ancient aqueous environments makes it ideal for advanced 
        sample return missions and detailed astrobiological investigations.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Priority Investigations
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Detailed organic compound analysis</li>
            <li>• Clay mineral biosignature search</li>
            <li>• Delta stratigraphy drilling</li>
            <li>• Paleoclimate reconstruction</li>
            <li>• Channel system chronology</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Sample Return Potential
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Clay-rich delta sediments</li>
            <li>• Inverted channel deposits</li>
            <li>• Organic-preserved samples</li>
            <li>• Varied depositional environments</li>
            <li>• Stratigraphic sequence samples</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/resources/7683/delta-structure-in-eberswalde-crater/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              NASA: Delta Structure in Eberswalde Crater
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/images/pia04293-eberswalde-delta-in-high-resolution/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              JPL: High-Resolution Delta Images
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Space_Science/Mars_Express/Rare_martian_lake_delta_spotted_by_Mars_Express"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              ESA: Rare Martian Lake Delta Discovery
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/2022JE007545"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Clay-Rich Sediment Biopreservation Study
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>